wasm alloc-pointer signed-cast trap (gm-method, plugkit-wasm-wrapper.js writeWasmInput/writeWasmBytes): a wasm i32 alloc-return with the high bit set (offset > 0x7fffffff, occurs once linear memory grows past ~2GB in a long session) arrives in JS as a NEGATIVE number; using it directly as a typed-array offset throws V8's 'Start offset <neg> is outside the bounds of the buffer', a deterministic long-session dispatch-blocking corruption. Fix: >>>0 coerces the i32 to its true unsigned offset before any Uint8Array construction. Always pair with guardWasmRange so a genuinely bad (ptr,len) raises the clean wasm-memory-read-out-of-bounds error instead of a raw typed-array throw. wasm-buffer-decode.test.js signedAllocPointerThrows/wrapperHasFix assert both the >>>0 coercion and the range-guard are present.